Dependansies:

  pip install adafruit-circuitpython-mcp9600 --break-system-packages
  sudo apt install i2c-tools

  sudo raspi-config

  Go to Interface Options → I2C → Enable.



Instructions:

Download the pakage and create a new folder for the programs, (Recommended to make a new folder under home directory.)
and extract the zip.Then go to dac server edit the direcory (Your_direcetory) to your directory.

After this Install Artisan for bookworm using flakpack.

  flatpak install flathub org.artisan_scope.artisan

  then run : 

  flatpak run org.artisan_scope.artisan

Setup a new crontab for the services:

Test them with:
  nohup python3 /home/pi/(YOUR_DIRECTORY)/sensor_server.py > /tmp/sensor_server.log 2>&1 &
  nohup python3 /home/pi/(YOUR_DIRECTORY)/dac_server.py > /tmp/dac_server.log 2>&1 &

After that reboot and make a new crontab:
  run: crontab -e
  Add this and save:
  
    @reboot nohup python3 /home/pi/(YOUR_DIRECTORY)/sensor_server.py > /tmp/sensor_server.log 2>&1 &
    @reboot nohup python3 /home/pi/(YOUR_DIRECTORY)/dac_server.py > /tmp/dac_server.log 2>&1 &

After that check if the addresses line up using:
  i2cdetect -y 1:

  The DAC is under 58.
  The two sensors is under 67 and 60.

In Artisan go enable advanced settings and navigate to the devices,section under setup, look for programs,

  under extrenal enable prog and set the input to where the programs are located, (the driver of this package) and select the tempreading.py as the input
  under out.py set it to the artisan_output.py.

Check if everything is do right in contab becuse the services are vital for Artisan to communicate with the hardware because of the nature of the install, 
Artisan is running in a sandboxed environment and isn't able to read or write to i2c devices.

These scripts bypass this by writing to extrenal txt files which Artisan can access.

